    "Many of the students who received their Ph.D.": [],
    "'s under him went on to become the most eminent art historians of twentieth-century and ranged widely in the methodology they employed in their own work.": [],
    "Some of his Ph.D.": [],
    "students developed methodologies divergent from W\u00f6lfflin's in their professional life: <a href=\"/antalf\">Frederick Antal</a>, <a href=\"/heidriche\">Ernst Heidrich</a>, Frankl, <a href=\"/stangea\">Alfred Stange</a>, <a href=\"/krautheimerr\">Richard Krautheimer</a> and <a href=\"/saxlf\">Fritz Saxl</a>; other students, such as <a href=\"/volkmannl\">Ludwig Volkmann</a> and Rosenberg, retained the master's methodology to the end.": [
