    "His dissertation on the psychological aspects to architectural appreciation is a synthesis of the major intellectual influences in his life: Burckhardt's broad view of what constitutes an historical document, a psychological approach to historical hermeneutics <em>Geisteswissenschaften</em> of Dilthey and the visual comparison technique of <a href=\"/morellig\">Giovanni Morelli</a>, to name but three.": [
        [
            141,
            151,
            [
                "Burkhart"
            ]
        ]
    ],
    "As a systematizer, he looked for a framework integrating empirical, psychological and visual elements.": [],
    "Art was a visual language, an independent mode of knowledge.": [],
    "Even art historians who differed greatly in their methodology, such as <a href=\"/panofskye\">Erwin Panofsky</a> adopted a hermeneutic framework as W\u00f6lfflin conspicuously did to hang their analysis.": [],
    "W\u00f6lfflin's most significant contribution to art-historical methodology may be in his side-by-side comparison technique of images.": [
